    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The context window is the maximum number of tokens a model can process in a single request — the sum of everything it reads (system prompt, conversation history, retrieved documents, the user's message) plus everything it generates (the response). Choosing a model with the right context length for your workload is not just about \"bigger is better.\" Long contexts cost more, can degrade recall quality, and often signal that a different architecture (retrieval, summarisation, chunking) would be more robust."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Context Window Layout and the Lost-in-the-Middle Effect"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Top: context window layout showing system prompt, conversation history, RAG context, user message, and output budget all fitting inside the context limit. Middle: context window sizes by model: 4k (legacy), 128k (GPT-4o, Sonnet), 200k (Claude Opus/Haiku), 1M+ (Gemini). Bottom: U-shaped recall curve showing high recall at the start and end of context but degraded recall in the middle — the lost-in-the-middle effect."
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The context window has a fixed capacity that input and output tokens must share. A 200k-token model with "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "max_tokens=8192",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " has roughly 192k tokens available for input. If the system prompt, history, and retrieved context together exceed that, the request fails with a context overflow error."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Lost-in-the-Middle Problem"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Empirical research (Liu et al., 2023) found that transformer models tend to recall information placed at the very beginning or very end of the context much better than information in the middle. A model given a 50-page document will often fail to retrieve a key fact on page 25 while reliably finding the same fact if it were on page 1 or page 50. This means stuffing a long context with relevant information is not equivalent to the model having actually read all of it."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Place the most critical instruction or key fact at the very start or very end of the context — never buried in the middle. This applies to system prompts, RAG chunks, and conversation history trimming."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
